{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Cg5LxkvWN2HBUC2vwnMbBR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Obtain pairwise comparisons between models\n     2→#'\n     3→#' @description\n     4→#'\n     5→#' Compare scores obtained by different models in a pairwise tournament. All\n     6→#' combinations of two models are compared against each other based on the\n     7→#' overlapping set of available forecasts common to both models.\n     8→#'\n     9→#' The input should be a `scores` object as produced by [score()]. Note that\n    10→#' adding additional unrelated columns can unpredictably change results, as\n    11→#' all present columns are taken into account when determining the set of\n    12→#' overlapping forecasts between two models.\n    13→#'\n    14→#' The output of the pairwise comparisons is a set of mean score ratios,\n    15→#' relative skill scores and p-values.\n    16→#'\n    17→#' \\if{html}{\n    18→#'   \\out{<div style=\"text-align: left\">}\n    19→#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}{options: style=\"width:750px;max-width:100\\%;\"}\n    20→#'   \\out{</div><p>}\n    21→#'   Illustration of the pairwise comparison process.\n    22→#'\n    23→#' }\n    24→#' \\if{latex}{\n    25→#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}\n    26→#' }\n    27→#'\n    28→#' *Mean score ratios*\n    29→#'\n    30→#' For every pair of two models, a mean score ratio is computed. This is simply\n    31→#' the mean score of the first model divided by the mean score of the second.\n    32→#' Mean score ratios are computed based on the set of overlapping forecasts\n    33→#' between the two models. That means that only scores for those targets are\n    34→#' taken into account for which both models have submitted a forecast.\n    35→#'\n    36→#' *(Scaled) Relative skill scores*\n    37→#'\n    38→#' The relative score of a model is the geometric mean of all mean score\n    39→#' ratios which involve that model.\n    40→#' If a baseline is provided, scaled relative skill scores will be calculated\n    41→#' as well. Scaled relative skill scores are simply the relative skill score of\n    42→#' a model divided by the relative skill score of the baseline model.\n    43→#'\n    44→#' *p-values*\n    45→#'\n    46→#' In addition, the function computes p-values for the comparison between two\n    47→#' models (again based on the set of overlapping forecasts). P-values can be\n    48→#' computed in two ways: based on a nonparametric Wilcoxon signed-rank test\n    49→#' (internally using [wilcox.test()] with `paired = TRUE`) or based on a\n    50→#' permutation test. The permutation test is based on the difference in mean\n    51→#' scores between two models. The default null hypothesis is that the mean score\n    52→#' difference is zero (see [permutation_test()]).\n    53→#' Adjusted p-values are computed by calling [p.adjust()] on the raw p-values.\n    54→#'\n    55→#' The code for the pairwise comparisons is inspired by an implementation by\n    56→#' Johannes Bracher.\n    57→#' The implementation of the permutation test follows the function\n    58→#' `permutationTest` from the `surveillance` package by Michael Höhle,\n    59→#' Andrea Riebler and Michaela Paul.\n    60→#'\n    61→#' @param compare Character vector with a single colum name that defines the\n    62→#'   elements for the pairwise comparison. For example, if this is set to\n    63→#'   \"model\" (the default), then elements of the \"model\" column will be\n    64→#'   compared.\n    65→#' @param by Character vector with column names that define further grouping\n    66→#'   levels for the pairwise comparisons. By default this is `NULL` and there\n    67→#'   will be one relative skill score per distinct entry of the column selected\n    68→#'   in `compare`. If further columns are given here, for example, `by =\n    69→#'   \"location\"` with `compare = \"model\"`, then one separate relative skill\n    70→#'   score is calculated for every model in every location.\n    71→#' @param metric A string with the name of the metric for which\n    72→#'   a relative skill shall be computed. By default this is either \"crps\",\n    73→#'   \"wis\" or \"brier_score\" if any of these are available.\n    74→#' @param baseline A string with the name of a model. If a baseline is\n    75→#'   given, then a scaled relative skill with respect to the baseline will be\n    76→#'   returned. By default (`NULL`), relative skill will not be scaled with\n    77→#'   respect to a baseline model.\n    78→#' @param ... Additional arguments for the comparison between two models. See\n    79→#'   [compare_forecasts()] for more information.\n    80→#' @inheritParams summarise_scores\n    81→#' @returns A data.table with the results of pairwise comparisons\n    82→#' containing the mean score ratios (`mean_scores_ratio`),\n    83→#' unadjusted (`pval`) and adjusted (`adj_pval`) p-values, and relative skill\n    84→#' values of each model (`..._relative_skill`). If a baseline model is given\n    85→#' then the scaled relative skill is reported as well\n    86→#' (`..._scaled_relative_skill`).\n    87→#' @importFrom data.table as.data.table data.table setnames copy\n    88→#' @importFrom stats sd rbinom wilcox.test p.adjust\n    89→#' @importFrom utils combn\n    90→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_subset assert_character assert_disjunct\n    91→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort cli_inform cli_warn\n    92→#' @export\n    93→#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n    94→#' @author Johannes Bracher, \\email{johannes.bracher@@kit.edu}\n    95→#' @keywords scoring\n    96→#' @examples\n    97→#' \\dontshow{\n    98→#'   data.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n    99→#' }\n   100→#'\n   101→#'\n   102→#' scores <- example_quantile |>\n   103→#'  as_forecast_quantile() |>\n   104→#'  score()\n   105→#'\n   106→#' pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(scores, by = \"target_type\")\n   107→#' pairwise2 <- get_pairwise_comparisons(\n   108→#'   scores, by = \"target_type\", baseline = \"EuroCOVIDhub-baseline\"\n   109→#' )\n   110→#'\n   111→#' library(ggplot2)\n   112→#' plot_pairwise_comparisons(pairwise, type = \"mean_scores_ratio\") +\n   113→#'   facet_wrap(~target_type)\n   114→\n   115→get_pairwise_comparisons <- function(\n   116→  scores,\n   117→  compare = \"model\",\n   118→  by = NULL,\n   119→  metric = intersect(c(\"wis\", \"crps\", \"brier_score\"), names(scores)),\n   120→  baseline = NULL,\n   121→  ...\n   122→) {\n   123→\n   124→  # input checks ---------------------------------------------------------------\n   125→  scores <- ensure_data.table(scores)\n   126→  # check that column in 'compare' is present\n   127→  assert(check_columns_present(scores, compare))\n   128→  # check that column(s) in `by` ar not in `compare`\n   129→  assert_disjunct(by, compare)\n   130→\n   131→  # we need the score names attribute to make sure we can determine the\n   132→  # forecast unit correctly, so here we check it exists\n   133→  metrics <- get_metrics.scores(scores, error = TRUE)\n   134→\n   135→  # check that metric is a subset of the scores and is of length 1\n   136→  assert_subset(metric, metrics, empty.ok = FALSE)\n   137→  assert_character(metric, len = 1)\n   138→\n   139→  # check that columns in 'by' are present\n   140→  #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   141→  if (length(by) > 0) {\n   142→    by_cols <- check_columns_present(scores, by)\n   143→    if (!isTRUE(by_cols)) {\n   144→      cli_abort(\n   145→        c(\n   146→          \"!\" = \"Not all columns specified in `by` are present: {.var {by_cols}}\"\n   147→        )\n   148→      )\n   149→      #nolint end\n   150→    }\n   151→  } else {\n   152→    ## set explicitly to character(0) in case it was given as NULL\n   153→    by <- character(0)\n   154→  }\n   155→\n   156→  # check that baseline exists\n   157→  comparators <- as.vector(unique(scores[[compare]]))\n   158→  assert_subset(baseline, comparators)\n   159→\n   160→  # check there are enough comparators\n   161→  if (length(setdiff(comparators, baseline)) < 2) {\n   162→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   163→    cli_abort(\n   164→      c(\n   165→        \"!\" = \"More than one non-baseline model is needed to compute\n   166→        pairwise compairisons.\"\n   167→      )\n   168→    )\n   169→    #nolint end\n   170→  }\n   171→\n   172→  # check that values of the chosen metric are not NA\n   173→  if (anyNA(scores[[metric]])) {\n   174→    scores <- scores[!is.na(scores[[metric]])]\n   175→    if (nrow(scores) == 0) {\n   176→      #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   177→      cli_abort(\n   178→        c(\n   179→          \"!\" = \"After removing {.val NA} values for {.var {metric}},\n   180→         no values were left.\"\n   181→        )\n   182→      )\n   183→    }\n   184→    cli_warn(\n   185→      c(\n   186→        \"!\" = \"Some values for the metric {.var {metric}}\n   187→         are NA. These have been removed.\",\n   188→        \"i\" = \"Maybe choose a different metric?\"\n   189→      )\n   190→    )\n   191→    #nolint end\n   192→  }\n   193→\n   194→  # check that all values of the chosen metric are positive\n   195→  if (any(sign(scores[[metric]]) < 0) && any(sign(scores[[metric]]) > 0)) {\n   196→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   197→    cli_abort(\n   198→      c(\n   199→        \"!\" = \"To compute pairwise comparisons, all values of {.var {metric}}\n   200→       must have the same sign.\"\n   201→      )\n   202→    )\n   203→    #nolint end\n   204→  }\n   205→\n   206→  # identify unit of single observation.\n   207→  forecast_unit <- get_forecast_unit(scores)\n   208→\n   209→  # if compare is equal to forecast_unit, then pairwise comparisons don't make\n   210→  # sense\n   211→  # if compare == forecast_unit then all relative skill scores will simply be 1.\n   212→  if (setequal(compare, forecast_unit)) {\n   213→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   214→    cli_warn(\n   215→      c(\n   216→        \"!\" = \"`compare` is set to the unit of a single forecast. This doesn't\n   217→            look right.\",\n   218→        \"i\" = \"All relative skill scores will be equal to 1.\"\n   219→      )\n   220→    )\n   221→    #nolint end\n   222→  } else if (setequal(c(compare, by), forecast_unit)) {\n   223→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   224→    cli_inform(\n   225→      c(\n   226→        \"!\" = \"relative skill can only be computed if the combination of\n   227→        `compare` and `by` is different from the unit of a single forecast.\",\n   228→        \"i\" = \"`by` was set to an empty character vector\"\n   229→      )\n   230→    )\n   231→    #nolint end\n   232→    by <- character(0)\n   233→  }\n   234→\n   235→  # do the pairwise comparison -------------------------------------------------\n   236→  # split data set into groups determined by 'by'\n   237→  split_scores <- split(scores, by = by)\n   238→\n   239→  results <- lapply(split_scores,\n   240→    FUN = function(scores) {\n   241→      pairwise_comparison_one_group(\n   242→        scores = scores,\n   243→        metric = metric,\n   244→        baseline = baseline,\n   245→        compare = compare,\n   246→        by = by,\n   247→        ...\n   248→      )\n   249→    }\n   250→  )\n   251→\n   252→  out <- data.table::rbindlist(results)\n   253→\n   254→  return(out[])\n   255→}\n   256→\n   257→#' @title Do pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts\n   258→#'\n   259→#' @description\n   260→#' This function does the pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts, but\n   261→#' multiple models involved. It gets called from [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   262→#' [get_pairwise_comparisons()] splits the data into arbitrary subgroups\n   263→#' specified by the user (e.g. if pairwise comparison should be done separately\n   264→#' for different forecast targets) and then the actual pairwise comparison for\n   265→#' that subgroup is managed from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()]. In order to\n   266→#' actually do the comparison between two models over a subset of common\n   267→#' forecasts it calls [compare_forecasts()].\n   268→#' @inherit get_pairwise_comparisons params return\n   269→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n   270→#' @importFrom data.table setnames\n   271→#' @keywords internal\n   272→\n   273→pairwise_comparison_one_group <- function(scores,\n   274→                                          metric,\n   275→                                          baseline,\n   276→                                          compare = \"model\",\n   277→                                          by,\n   278→                                          ...) {\n   279→  if (!(compare %in% names(scores))) {\n   280→    cli_abort(\n   281→      \"pairwise comparisons require a column as given by `compare`\"\n   282→    )\n   283→  }\n   284→\n   285→  # get list of models\n   286→  comparators <- unique(scores[[compare]])\n   287→\n   288→  # if there aren't enough models to do any comparison, abort\n   289→  if (length(comparators) < 2) {\n   290→    cli_abort(\n   291→      c(\"!\" = \"There are not enough comparators to do any comparison\")\n   292→    )\n   293→  }\n   294→\n   295→  # create a data.frame with results\n   296→  # we only need to do the calculation once, because for the ratio that\n   297→  # should just be the inverse and for the permutation the result should\n   298→  # be the same\n   299→\n   300→  # set up initial data.frame with all possible pairwise comparisons\n   301→  combinations <- data.table::as.data.table(t(combn(comparators, m = 2)))\n   302→  colnames(combinations) <- c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\")\n   303→\n   304→  combinations[, c(\"ratio\", \"pval\") := compare_forecasts(\n   305→    compare = compare,\n   306→    scores = scores,\n   307→    name_comparator1 = ..compare,\n   308→    name_comparator2 = compare_against,\n   309→    metric = metric,\n   310→    ...\n   311→  ),\n   312→  by = seq_len(NROW(combinations))\n   313→  ]\n   314→\n   315→  combinations <- combinations[order(ratio)]\n   316→  combinations[, adj_pval := p.adjust(pval)]\n   317→\n   318→  # mirror computations\n   319→  combinations_mirrored <- data.table::copy(combinations)\n   320→  setnames(combinations_mirrored,\n   321→    old = c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\"),\n   322→    new = c(\"compare_against\", \"..compare\")\n   323→  )\n   324→  combinations_mirrored[, ratio := 1 / ratio]\n   325→\n   326→  # add a one for those that are the same\n   327→  combinations_equal <- data.table::data.table(\n   328→    ..compare = comparators,\n   329→    compare_against = comparators,\n   330→    ratio = 1,\n   331→    pval = 1,\n   332→    adj_pval = 1\n   333→  )\n   334→  result <- data.table::rbindlist(list(\n   335→    combinations,\n   336→    combinations_mirrored,\n   337→    combinations_equal\n   338→  ),\n   339→  use.names = TRUE\n   340→  )\n   341→\n   342→  # make result character instead of factor\n   343→  result[, `:=`(\n   344→    ..compare = as.character(..compare),\n   345→    compare_against = as.character(compare_against)\n   346→  )]\n   347→\n   348→  setnames(result, old = \"..compare\", new = compare)\n   349→\n   350→  # calculate relative skill as geometric mean\n   351→  # small theta is again better (assuming that the score is negatively oriented)\n   352→  result[, `:=`(\n   353→    theta = geometric_mean(ratio)\n   354→  ),\n   355→  by = compare,\n   356→  ]\n   357→\n   358→  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n   359→    baseline_theta <- unique(result[get(compare) == baseline, ]$theta)\n   360→    if (length(baseline_theta) == 0) {\n   361→      cli_abort(\n   362→        \"Baseline comparator {.var {baseline}} missing.\"\n   363→      )\n   364→    }\n   365→    result[, rel_to_baseline := theta / baseline_theta]\n   366→  }\n   367→\n   368→  # remove all the rows that are not present in by before merging\n   369→  cols_to_keep <- unique(c(by, compare))\n   370→  cols_to_remove <- colnames(scores)[!(colnames(scores) %in% cols_to_keep)]\n   371→  scores[, eval(cols_to_remove) := NULL]\n   372→  scores <- unique(scores)\n   373→  # allow.cartesian needs to be set as sometimes rows will be duplicated a lot\n   374→  out <- merge(scores, result, by = compare, all = TRUE)\n   375→\n   376→  # rename ratio to mean_scores_ratio\n   377→  data.table::setnames(out,\n   378→    old = c(\"ratio\", \"theta\"),\n   379→    new = c(\n   380→      \"mean_scores_ratio\",\n   381→      paste(metric, \"relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n   382→    )\n   383→  )\n   384→  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n   385→    data.table::setnames(out,\n   386→      old = \"rel_to_baseline\",\n   387→      new = paste(metric, \"scaled_relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n   388→    )\n   389→  }\n   390→\n   391→  return(out[])\n   392→}\n   393→\n   394→#' @title Compare a subset of common forecasts\n   395→#'\n   396→#' @description\n   397→#' This function compares two comparators based on the subset of forecasts for which\n   398→#' both comparators have made a prediction. It gets called\n   399→#' from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()], which handles the\n   400→#' comparison of multiple comparators on a single set of forecasts (there are no"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RZvW74s2hFGwXoSCtH5UzL","session_id":"808715c1-0a39-4dc0-b462-320649655d88","uuid":"afe4e909-01e7-4947-98bd-b18c848d8e25"}
